tip.text: This West Village corner café by the team behind Odeon in Tribeca caters to a very discerning crowd—and it's consistently packed, thanks to its comfortable-classy ambience.
The secret to Spoon is to arrive late (2 p.m. is perfect) and linger long enough for them to start handing out the morning's pastries, like a bonus brunch for those who slept in.
We're pretty lazy about going to synagogue, but we're pretty sure that R&D’s smoked fish platter counts as a spiritual experience.

formattedAddress: 179 E Houston St (btwn Allen & Orchard St)

tip.text: "To sit at the eight-seat counter is to dive headlong into an eight- to ten-course improv comedy show, as chef Zaiyu Hasegawa and his crew trot out surprise after kooky surprise." - Peter Jon Lindberg
“It’s a glass-enclosed dining room atop an olive tree–covered hill outside the city. The food is simple but extraordinary.” - Anita Lo, chef/owner of Annisa
“The best seat in the house is a round table just inside the courtyard, giving a unique vantage point on happenings both inside and out.” - Steve Wilson
“I’m happy to wait in line to get my hands on my favorite Sqirl triumvirate: sorrel pesto rice bowl, brioche toast with ricotta and Blenheim apricot jam, with a turmeric tonic.” - Fiorella Valdesolo
“Briny half-shells most likely harvested that morning, note-perfect lobster rolls, a killer wine list, and all sorts of unexpected treats on the daily menu.” - Peter Jon Lindberg
“The beauty, tradition, and craftsmanship of Scandinavian food. The best seat is at the bar.” - Marcus Samuelsson, chef, restaurateur, and cookbook author
“Gabriela Cámara’s ex­traordinary restaurant is always my first stop. It feels like the city’s dining room.” - Alice Waters
“Le Bernardin proves every day that fine dining can still be relevant and enjoyable. There is no better food, service, or wine program.” - Anthony Bourdain
“I’ve only had 0.01 percent of America’s burgers, but this is by far the best I’ve ever tasted.” - Peter Jon Lindberg

formattedAddress: 800 W Randolph St (at S Halsted St)

tip.text: “Tyson Cole is the patriarch of the Austin food scene, and 13 years in, Uchi is still one of the great Japanese restaurants in the country.” - Peter Jon Lindberg
“My favorites: the chickpea fries, pig’s head, and carrots with goat cheese ricotta. There’s also sweeping views of Table Mountain. Make reservations months in advance.” - Cherae Robinson
"While the menu changes daily, the organizing principle—‘raw,’ ‘smaller,’ and ‘bigger’—remains the same.” - Pilar Guzmán
“Get the Forward to the Past tasting menu, which might include moose milk or the caviar of an albino sturgeon.” - Anya von Bremzen, food critic and memoirist
“Every glass of wine and beer is produced in Bolivia. The caiman sashimi is caught by indigenous Tacana hunters within a quota system that allows populations to stay healthy.” - Nicholas Gill
“Ben Shewry’s cuisine is thought-provoking and unusual... in a good way.” - Simon Rogan, chef/owner of L’Enclume in Cartmel, England
Though it has grown beyond its beginnings as a wildly popular pop-up breakfast spot, Williamsburg favorite Egg still sees a crowd of people waiting to get inside on weekends.
There are brunch spots that are ideal for boozing, and those better for nursing a night of overindulgence. Prime Meats, luckily, fits nicely into both categories.
Get yourself to Red Hook, order the All American or the huevos rancheros, and keep your joy at having discovered the best brunch spot in Brooklyn to yourself.
We seem to have a thing for brasseries—though this one is decidedly American, with more comfort food than a Southern diner, like the guilt-inducing breakfast pot pie and jalapeño cheddar grits.
This is the kind of place you take your mom when she comes to visit, and also the kind of place where it’s not weird to order three helpings of lemon-ricotta pancakes.
Balthazar somehow fashioned a magical spot in which Paris and New York embrace like lost sisters; nearly two decades on, it's still the ultimate Manhattan brunch rendezvous.
Andrew Carmellini’s brasserie is a love letter to all things French, from the expertly baked brioche and pain au chocolat for sale at the in-house boulangerie, to the Bloody Marie at brunch.

formattedAddress: 380 Lafayette St (btwn Great Jones & E 4th St)

tip.text: Before Santa Fe’s ski basin draws a winter crowd, it erupts in golden aspens. See the sight yourself by climbing the Aspen Vista Trail.
Every fall, hikers (and photographers) take to Dyke Trail—a six-miler that meanders the sea of yellow and crosses the rocky ridge from which it takes its name. (You can drive or bike, if you prefer.)
On this 5.5 mile loop, you'll see a little bit of everything: snow-capped peaks; a rushing creek; two glacially-formed lakes; wide-open terrain; and, of course, bright yellow aspen.
Head up Bald Mountain on this 0.9-mile loop, where you’ll see wildflowers, aspen, and views of the Jordanelle Reservoir. History buffs, keep your eyes open for old mining equipment along the way.
Maroon Bells is home to hikes for every kind of nature enthusiast. Don't forget to look down: Maroon Lake reflects the Bells, wildflowers, and aspens galore.
Here, you’re surrounded by trees with turning leaves; roaring waters; and fishermen taking advantage of one of the best spots in the region.
The steep, strenuous hike is one of the most common in the Northeast for more reasons than just its accessibility: Strategic rock scrambling rewards with panoramic views of the Hudson River Valley.

contact.facebookName: New York - New Jersey Trail Conference

tip.text: One of the country's most-visited national parks provides fall sights aplenty: namely, the sought-after leaves of red, orange, and yellow.
Summit via Sunset Ridge, which practically guarantees views. Once you're up top, look west toward the colors of Lake Champlain. Dreading the hike down? Don't—you can take a chairlift.
Carriage roads, waterfalls, and the view from the top—Vermont’s Green Mountains, the Catskills, and—on a clear day—New Hampshire’s White Mountains—reveal what all the fuss is about.
Climb up to Sky Top Tower at Lake Mohonk, off Route 299, from where you'll be able to see reds, oranges, and yellows spreading out over not one, but six states.
A network of hiking trails of varying difficulties offer serene walks through the woods and a number of lookout points over the Hudson Valley.
All the fruit and vegetables come from a farm they own. The spaghetti alle zucchine with clams in particular is amazing. The is atmosphere casual and warm, while doling out impressive daily specials.
Rise 34 stories above to find this extraordinary chill-out spot, spanning the entire rooftop of the Four Seasons Mumbai. Watch the city lights illuminate the night sky over the Arabian Sea.

formattedAddress: 114 Dr. E. Moses Road,  Worli (at Drainage Channel Road)

tip.text: This beachfront rooftop restaurant and bar at the Anantara Seminyak Resort & Spa is the perfect place to transition from your journey of Zen back to big-city fast-living.
Chile’s bar of the moment is this under-the-radar rooftop lounge at Tinto Boutique Hotel. You can access for nightcaps as a non-member after dining at Restaurant 040 on the hotel's lower floor.
The world’s highest rooftop bar is exactly what bucket-list dreams are made of. On the 118th floor of the Ritz-Carlton, you’ll bask in extreme views of Hong Kong Island while sipping an HK Skyline.

location.address: 118/F, The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong, 1 Austin Rd W
formattedAddress: 118/F, The Ritz-Carlton Hong Kong, 1 Austin Rd W

tip.text: Toast to the romance and beauty of the City of Light, marveling at panoramas of the Eiffel Tower and Paris’ famed rooftops at this vintage aviation-themed lounge crowning the Peninsula Paris.
This small, secret rooftop of the restored Casa Gangotena mansion peers over Plaza San Francisco in the center of Quito's colonial Old Town, the world’s first UNESCO World Heritage Site.
Gaze at the Sea of Cortez, the cactus-speckled landscape, and the iconic El Arco natural rock formation while sipping new cocktail creations by award-winning mixologist Osvaldo Vazquez.

formattedAddress: 23455 Cabo San Lucas, Baja California Sur

tip.text: Discover the best views—and drinks—on the summit of the Ritz-Carlton Shanghai, Pudong, 58 floors above the bustling metropolis and overlooking the Huangpu River, the Bund, and the evolving skyline.

formattedAddress: 58/F, The Ritz-Carlton Shanghai Pudong, 8 Century Ave. (at Lujiazui Ring Rd.)
location.address: 58/F, The Ritz-Carlton Shanghai Pudong, 8 Century Ave.

tip.text: Baba Nest is a floating bar in the center of a mountaintop infinity pool, strewn with comfy, oversized pillows and serving Sri-jitos (Sri Panwa’s fabulous take on the mojito).
Jetting 61 stories towards the heavens atop the Banyan Tree Bangkok with 360-degree views extending to the horizon in all directions, it’s like hovering over Bangkok’s dazzling cityscape.

formattedAddress: Banyan Tree Hotel Bangkok (61st Fl., Rooftop)

tip.text: Lake Powell is an impressive man-made reservoir that attracts millions of tourists every year, thanks in large part to its convenient proximity to natural bridges, dams, and Grand-ish canyons.
Bear Lake in the Kenai Fjords National Park manages to stand out, thanks to its massive glaciers, year-round water sports (kayaking, dog mushing), and occasional viewings of the Northern Lights.
At 1,943 feet, Crater Lake is the deepest lake in the U.S., and one of its most stunning. There are no streams or rivers feeding it—the lake is the product of pure glacial runoff and precipitation.
Mono is renowned for its abnormally high amount of salt—about twice as much as the ocean—and creepy/cool tufa formations (built-up limestone formed by carbonate minerals in water).
Original brick arches and terra cotta columns comprise a roof of century-old ruins. You’ll catch a glimpse of Freedom Tower, but it's more likely that your eyes will be on the crowd.
Come evening, head to the wraparound terrace at Dream Downtown, which has vistas of the Hudson River and sparkling Empire State Building. The “Strawberry Fields” is our drink of choice.
At this grand, industrial chic fusion of indoor- outdoor space, and the glow of the Empire State Building join forces to play Cupid. The strong cocktails also help.
Unpretentious fun is the theme at this bar and lounge above the Park South Hotel. The gregarious crowd, which spans all demographics, can’t get enough of the creative, spirit-forward cocktails.

The Drift reopened for summer season in June 2016 with quite possibly the summer’s most delicious and Instagram-worthy cocktail: “frosé”—rosé sorbet and sparkling rosé topped with a skewer of berries.
Head past the Rodins and up to the fifth-floor garden atop the Metropolitan Museum of Art for magnificent views of Central Park.

contact.facebookName: The Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York

tip.text: The wraparound views of the Manhattan skyline and Jersey City are sublime as are the pitcher-sized libations. Arrive at 4 p.m. for a chance at grabbing a coveted chair or couch.
PH-D Terrace is one of the city’s more intimate and well-decorated rooftops, strewn with colorful designer cushions. Get the “Pomegranate Rickey.”
Here, you'll find no DJs, and no sloppy folk: Instead, there are twinkling lights, fire pits, artisanal cocktails, and unobstructed panoramas to help you revel in big city beauty.
Get a table on the East Terrace, where you can overlook the shops of Fifth Avenue from 23 stories up.  Settle in and order a “Ning Sling,” a gin-based passion fruit mojito topped with lychees.

formattedAddress: The Peninsula New York, 700 5th Ave, New York (at W 55th St)
location.address: The Peninsula New York, 700 5th Ave, New York

tip.text: If you want to see volcanoes, glaciers, and rain forests all in one place, just add Lake Clark to your travel list. You're almost guaranteed to spot some foraging brown bears along the shore.
The surrounding glaciers grind rocks into a powder that infiltrates the water, giving it that otherworldly color. The reservoir is a popular kayaking and hiking location.
Lake McDonald is one of the glimmering crown jewels of Montana's Glacier National Park. It's relatively small, but it more than compensates with its pebble beaches and glacial reflections.
Covering parts of both Texas and Louisiana, Caddo is the poster child for southern lakes. The Spanish moss, wide cyprus trees, and sporadic alligator sightings all help add to its down-home charm.
Since the late 19th century, the spot has been a popular retreat for summer sports enthusiasts, millionaires (John D. Rockefeller), and artists (Georgia O'Keefe).
Surrounded by mountains and dense forests, Avalanche Lake could pass as cozy...almost. Let us not forget the glacial water, frozen winters, and relatively common avalanches (hence the name).
The Lake is Great due to its diverse and lovely geology, from islands with mini-lakes with mini-islands to waterfalls to impressive rock formations.

Redfish Lake got its name from the massive amounts of sockeye salmon that migrated 900 miles there from the Pacific Ocean. The once bustling lake perfectly reflects the surrounding Sawtooth Mountains.
It's the largest alpine lake in North America and was formed millions of years ago during the Ice Age. It receives worldwide acclaim for scenic mountain views, luxe ski resorts and Nevada casinos.
The water is simultaneously clear and turquoise (due to dissolving carbonate minerals), and the small basin is fed by several waterfalls in Glenwood Canyon.
Crystal clear water with geysers and —Yellowstone Lake is definitely a beauty to behold. It's proximity to colorful hot springs make it a popular spot for both kayakers and leisurely walkers.
Known collectively as "The Pearl of the Indian Ocean" Bazaruto is most easily reached by air from Johannesburg to Vilanculos, and then onward by small aircraft or boat.
Set around dramatic limestone formations, El Nido boasts the finest and whitest sand you’ll ever see. The water is so blindingly blue it makes the Caribbean Sea look murky in comparison.
With its jet-black shore, lapis lazuli waters and thick, jungle-like foliage, Honokalani Beach is a photographer’s dream. Lie lazily on the “sand”—actually made up of of tiny lava pebbles.
The beach is long and broad with velvety sand and shocking blue water, and it's fringed with swaying palms and leafy takamaka trees. It’s also framed by enormous granite boulders on either side.
Think cumin-colored sand bordered by soaring, vegetation-cloaked cliffs—and, most times, not a soul in sight.
One of the world's best places to watch big wave surfing in winter, the water here becomes as calm as a lake in summer and is a great place for snorkeling.
The beach scene is a bustling one year-round on the mile-long stretch of sea and sand that inspired one of the most famous bossa nova ditties of all time.
A long, thin stretch of perfect sand and crystal clear water in a thousand shades of blue, make this one of the Caribbean's top beaches.

venue.name: Bahia de la Chiva (aka Blue Beach)

tip.text: Young, attractive surfers and paragliders make this one of the coolest beaches in all of Brazil, the beach is only 16kms east of the attractive town of Florianopolis.
At the bottom, you’re rewarded with a mile-long black volcanic sand beach bordered by 2000-foot cliff walls and backed by thick rainforest.
The mile-long stretch of silky, powder-white sand slopes gently into a shallow emerald lagoon, and is backed by a thick curtain of palms and tropical foliage.
Jaw-dropping views of the rugged, jungle peaks of neighboring Phi Phi Leh island, great snorkeling, and a laid-back vibe contribute to the overall attraction of Long Beach.

formattedAddress: จังหวัดกระบี่

tip.text: Lined with tiny stalls selling shell souvenirs and jewelry under rows and rows of palms, it's relative emptiness and laid-back atmosphere is paradise imagined.
Horseshoe Bay has a hidden secret – Port Royal Cove – with shallow water perfect for young kids, and dramatic rock formations that compliment wonderfully soft, pink sand.
North of the Sofitel towards the airport, Temae has a famous surf break but is still safe for swimming off one of the widest stretches of sand in all of French Polynesia.
Of the 33 pristine beaches on Anguilla, Barnes Bay seems to have the softest sand imagineable (no rocks or shells) and far fewer crowds than at hopping Sandy Ground or resort-heavy Shoal Bay East.
Blinky Beach boasts requisite powder-white sand and azure waters. Behind it, you’ll find tall dunes dotted with prickly spinifex and wild daisies.
Lopes Mendes is two miles of unspoiled, deserted, powder-white sand that leads to some of the world’s clearest, most crystalline waters.
Australia is known for its spectacular beaches, including this stunning colored beach on Fraser Island. The entire island is World Heritage-listed for being the largest sand island in the world.
Calm, clear water and a 225-yard-long Underwater Trail for superb snorkeling are big draws, as are hiking trails up and into the surrounding greenery.

formattedAddress: St John Island Saint John Island 00830

tip.text: If you have the patience to go alllll the way down to the last 12 miles of Long Island’s South Fork, you'll be rewarded with this pristine peninsula.
A great place to go especially since the Salt Hotel group renovated The Chequit, a 37-room inn that retains its Victorian charm without hitting you over the head with it.
Main Beach in East Hampton  has topped a national best beach list—and what's not to like?
The island has long been a bike-friendly haven & alternative to the Hamptons. And Robert Moses State Park on the western stretch delivers the best in sand and scenery, lighthouse included.
Rebuilt in 2013 post-Hurricane Sandy, the Long Beach boardwalk is just one reason to take the easy 50-minute train ride from Manhattan out. The surf-able waves are another.

Visiting the Brooklyn boardwalk, eating a Nathan’s hot dog, riding the Thunderbolt rollercoaster in Luna Park, & carving out a spot on the beach is still an everyone-should-try-it New York experience.
This mile-long of Pelham Bay Park is the Bronx’s only public beach, and it’s a popular spot. It has snack bars & picnic areas, two playgrounds, and 26 courts for basketball, volleyball, and handball.
Jacob Riis Park is part of Gateway National Recreation Area, with history that dates back to 1912.
Take the $7-each-way NYC Beach Bus from Union Square or Brooklyn, rent a surfboard, then stop for tacos at the Rockaway Beach Surf Club, and check out art at Topless gallery.
Sandy Hook has something for everyone: wide, sandy beaches manned by an army of lifeguards; fishing and nature walks; and history (the oldest operating lighthouse in the U.S.).

formattedAddress: Sandy Hook Visitor Center (Gateway National Receation Area)

tip.text: Home of a revitalized boardwalk, classic rock at the Stone Pony, a growing foodie scene, and the brand-new Asbury Hotel with its very buzzy rooftop bar (locals love it).
Now 80 years old, Great Smoky is a tribute to natural grandeur, and to the pioneers of our first frontier.
Mountain ranges, over 130 lakes, and 26 glaciers—what's left of 100 or more.
Erupting since 1983, Kilauea is one of Earth's most spectacular phenomena.
Skyscraping peaks and delicate alpine tundra, bighorn sheep scaling jagged cliffs, and glacier-carved valleys.
Spectacular 277-mile-long, 15-mile-wide, mile-deep Colorado River canyon.
The 91-mile Park Road accesses a vast subarctic wilderness with North America's tallest peak and an abundance of wildlife.
Blueberries and blue bloods, misty islands, spruce and pine forest, craggy coastlines.
Spacious valleys, towering rock domes, crystalline rivers, thundering waterfalls, giant sequoias.
A wonderland of geothermal phenomena and wildlife.
Rugged coast, glacier-capped mountains, and temperate—and largely roadless—rain forests.
